    </description>
    <baseline year="2020">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">0 Number of policy engagement actions conducted
0 number of documented program actions that contribute to policy formulation to promote plastics recovery</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1 Policy engagement action (Integrated Waste Management Fair) undertaken
2 program actions documented (reports) that contribute to policy formulation to promote plastics recovery</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1 Policy engagement action (Integrated Waste Management Fair) conducted;
2 program related documentations/publication that contributes to policy formulation produced. 

For the year under review, UNDP conducted the first ever Ghana Integrated Waste Management Fair, also dubbed &#x201C;Ghana Waste Fair&#x201D; in July. The Fair had over 60 exhibitors, showcasing innovative solutions with different materials in transition and along the value chain. The fair also had thematic TED-TALK events, where over 150 participants (virtually and physically) featured issues from data and use in waste management, innovative solutions and impact of the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge, green finance, how financial and technical resources from development partners and donors can be leveraged to upscale integrated solutions for waste management, business clinics. A school&#x2019;s competition that was part of the fair concluded with St. Catherine Senior High School, Obuasi Senior High Technical School and Methodist Senior High School were awarded cash prizes to implement innovative solutions for waste management in their schools. Following the fair, a technical meeting with experts has enabled the drafting of policy and program recommendations and actions for policy advocacy with relevant government ministries and building partnerships for program implementation.

Two publications, the Integrated Waste Management Fair Report and the follow up actions for policy and program implementation from the Waste Fair were produced and shared with relevant government institutions to inform policy formulation.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">2 Number of documented program actions that contribute to policy formulation to promote plastics recovery in Ghana</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">2 program actions that has policy implication documented and shared with relevant government institutions, including MESTI to influence policy for the year under review. These were firstly an awareness campaign actions that highlighted the important role of waste collectors in society and during the COVID-19 response, leading to the mobilization of additional resources to provide PPEs to waste collectors.Secondly, UNDP provided business service support to a cohort of businesses in the plastic waste value chain who were winners in the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge to identify and implement set of actions for improving the business of plastic waste recovery and this has informed policy makers on how best to provide business service support for enterprises in the plastic waste recovery value chain.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
